ey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rugeley","meanings":["English: locative name from Rugeley (Staffs). The place, recorded as Rugelie in 1086 (   Domesday Book  ), is named with Old English  <i>hrycg</i> ‘ridge’ +  <i>lēah</i> ‘(woodland) clearing, glade’."]}]},{"name":"Humphrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Humphry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfrey","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":63,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":72,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Humphrey Ruggeley was born in 1486, in England, his father, William Rugeley, was 25 and his mother, Alice Clarkson, was 16. He married Margaret Hussey about 1518, in Longdon, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1558, in Longdon, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1486–1558":"1486–1558","1490–1554":"1490–1554","1511–1581":"1511–1581","1498–1558":"1498–1558","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1530–1600":"1530–1600","1461–1510":"1461–1510","1470–1510":"1470–1510","1461":"1461","1581":"1581","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","about 1518":"umbes 1518","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1511":"1511","1510":"1510","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","1498":"1498","1486":"1486","1530":"1530","about 1520":"umbes 1520","1549":"1549","after 1510":"pärast 1510","Longdon, Staffordshire, England":"Longdon, Staffordshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1486–1558":"1486–1558","1490–1554":"1490–1554","1511–1581":"1511–1581","1498–1558":"1498–1558","1520–Female":"1520–Kuollut","1530–1600":"1530–1600","1461–1510":"1461–1510","1470–1510":"1470–1510","1461":"1461","1581":"1581","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","about 1518":"noin 1518","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1511":"1511","1510":"1510","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","1498":"1498","1486":"1486","1530":"1530","about 1520":"noin 1520","1549":"1549","after 1510":"1510 jälkeen","Longdon, Staffordshire, England":"Longdon, Staffordshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1486–1558":"1486–1558","1490–1554":"1490–1554","1511–1581":"1511–1581","1498–1558":"1498–1558","1520–Female":"1520–D